review_blob: Poured a little fizzy. Very pale, nice hop aroma, reminds me of a Kolsch more than anything. Crisp and easy drinking.
beer_name: Black Star Co-op Pub & Brewery id

review_blob: A decent "gateway" beer that I cant blame them for brewing.  Not a thing wrong with it -- no rough edges, good balance and finishes with a little hops in the back.
Light in body, similar to High Esteem, but with very nice hop aroma.  A very good session beer the hophead.
beer_name: Black Star Co-op Pub & Brewery Nemesis

review_blob: On draft -- pale and a bit hazy, a little hint of funk on the nose.  Egad -- its sour!  Yeah, kids, have another sip, yeah. . . yeah . . . yeah!  A terrific style for Texas, and ABW has a winner.  Not especially complex but very refreshing and balanced out just right.  Can it, and Ill fill my cooler!

Nice and refreshing, well balanced, but quite different than my gold standard of this style, Saison Dupont.  On tap, it was low in effervescence.  Pale gold with a little haze.  Little bit of vanilla in the aroma.  Wet mouth feel with nice subtle peach flavors up front, followed by a nicely balanced hop astringency.  Yeasty flavors are there, but not especially prominent.  In the end, Id say its a little closer to a Belgian blonde, but hey it works for me!

beer_brewer_name: Uncle Billys Brew & Que Smokehouse & Brewery
review_blob: Ready to try some Belgian styles?  This is a good place to start.  Nice, clean, and refreshing.  Yeast flavors are there but not prominent.  Good balance and at 4.8% ABV, it wont put you under the table.

Real Ales Sisyphus has always been a bit too sticky sweet for me, but the oak aging that transforms it into The Kraken adds several layers of flavors that balance out just right.  The sweetness is still there but balanced by a bit of winey acidity. Beautiful!

beer_brewer_name: Uncle Billys Brew & Que Smokehouse & Brewery
review_blob: This is a near perfect summer brew.  Light and refreshing but not at all wimpy.  Great fresh grain flavors perfectly balanced with a crisp hop finish.
Very nice yeasty aroma -- think Belgian Tripel.  As for taste, however, the hops definitely sings lead here.  The yeasty flavors are some talented backup singers that have some great solo potential.

This was a truly fine imperial stout, and then JK threw in their wild yeast -- woah!  Old Rasputin, my gold standard imperial stout, seems positively frumpy now.  This is is a slightly sweet imperial stout -- brewed by your crazy aunt!  The sour flavors bubble just below the surface of the big black malt flavor and cut the sweetness just right.  Let your Flat Tire drinking friend have a sip of THIS!
beer_name: Jester King Black Metal Farmhouse Imperial Stout

review_blob: On tap at the Draught House, Austin.  Fresh aroma with a hint of biscuit and a bit of grassy hops.  Nice wet mouthfeel with some malty notes gives way to a full, long lasting, assertive hop finish.  Ive drifted away from hoppy beers in the last few years because so many just beat you to death with hops.  I could drink a few of these.

beer_brewer_name: Uncle Billys Brew & Que Smokehouse & Brewery
review_blob: Texas first brewpub Waterloo Brewing had an "Eds Best Bitter", and I feel certain this is an homage -- if not a revival.  This is a fine session beer for the folks having a quiet witty conversation in the corner of the bar.  Very true to the syle, its not too bitter, not too nutty, just a great well-balanced beer.

Raspberry, raspberry, raspberry!  The fruit flavor is very nicely rendered with just the right amount of sour and tartness.  Unfortunately, it overpowers all the other flavors.  Dial it down a notch or two, and itll be a winner!
beer_name: Black Star Co-op Pub & Brewery Rebellious Dockhand

beer_brewer_name: Uncle Billys Brew & Que Smokehouse & Brewery
review_blob: Great fresh hop aroma, deep red color.  Nice soft malt profile -- a good bit of sweetness but not nutty.  Good balance against an assertive hop finish.  The alcohol level (8%) was pretty apparent but not unpleasant.  Very nice!
One of the best balanced Pilsners Ive ever had.  Theres some nice malt complexity in there set against a nice crisp finish.  Forget Real Ales Firemans 4 and have one of these!

A bit of fresh hop aroma.  Color a little on the light side like a Maibock.  Smooth malt flavor initially gives way to a slightly nutty and moderately bitter finish.  Not bad but not especially distinctinve.  I wish theyd gone for a straight Maibock -- its a great but under-produced style.

Draft arrived with a decent head that hung around for the first few sips.  Mild roasted aroma, but much bigger flavor than I expected.  This has more dark roasted flavors (black patent malt?) than many porters or stouts.  Not bad and an interesting variation on the style.

Very nice hop aroma, but wait, its black!  Hey, you got chocolate in my peanut butter!  It really does work -- theres quite a bit of IBUs in there, but Id say the dark roasted flavors are playing lead here.  They are the first flavors that hit me and the ones that lingered very nicely.  Oh, but theres the hops on the finish, too.  Not for the newbie, but if you want a very well crafted civil union - go get one!

Nice carmel aroma, thick mouthfeel.  Mine had a nice low level of carbonation.  Nice and malty but not cloyingly sweet.  Not especially complex, but very pleasant.  The alcohol level was not apparent in the nose or the flavor so it could sneak up on you!  Good show on this one, Independence!
beer_name: Independence Brewing Brewluminati: Kill Shot Scotch Ale

review_blob: A nice, tidy amber with some good nutty notes -- very accessible.  Im not sure its quite big enough to be an ESB -- I think its more in league with Saint Arnolds Amber, Live Oak Big Bark, and Fat Tire.  Stop your friend from ordering a Shiner Bock next time, and get him/her one of these instead!
